# Routing Architecture

This prototyping environment uses React Router v6 with HashRouter. Pages are accessed via hash URLs (e.g., `http://localhost:5174/#/home`).

## How It Works

- `src/App.tsx` is the router shell — skills manage it, designers don't edit it directly
- Each page lives in `src/pages/[Name].tsx`
- Each page has its own stylesheet at `src/styles/[Name].module.css`
- Routes are defined in `App.tsx` — either in the `APP_PAGES` array (for app pages) or as standalone `<Route>` elements (for shell-level pages like onboarding)

## Two Types of Pages

### Shell Pages (top-level)
Pages outside the app navigation: `/home`, `/workspace`, `/onboarding`. These are defined as standalone `<Route>` elements in `App.tsx`.

### App Pages (within AppShell navigation)
Pages accessed through the SubNav sidebar: `/app/accounting/bank-transactions`, `/app/sales-payments/invoices`, etc. These are registered in the `APP_PAGES` array in `App.tsx` and render inside the FusionShell layout.

Any unmatched `/app/*` path renders a `NotFoundPage` placeholder that tells the designer how to create the page.

## Adding a New App Page

When a designer asks to create a page for a SubNav item (e.g., "build the Bank Transactions page"), do all four of these things in order:

1. Create `src/pages/[Name]Page.tsx` — the page component
2. Create `src/styles/[Name]Page.module.css` — the page stylesheet
3. Add an import to `App.tsx`: `import [Name]Page from './pages/[Name]Page'`
4. Add an entry to `APP_PAGES` in `App.tsx`: `{ path: 'section/page-name', component: [Name]Page }`

The `path` value in `APP_PAGES` is relative to `/app/` — so `'accounting/bank-transactions'` maps to the URL `/app/accounting/bank-transactions`.

After creating a page, always tell the designer: "Your new page is at `http://localhost:5174/#/app/[section]/[page-name]`"

### App Page Path Convention

App paths follow the SubNav structure defined in `src/components/FusionShell/SubNav.tsx`:

```
/app/accounting/bank-transactions
/app/accounting/chart-of-accounts
/app/sales-payments/invoices
/app/expenses-bills/vendors
/app/customer-hub/customers
/app/team/employees
/app/time/time-entries
/app/projects/projects
/app/inventory/inventory
/app/business-tax/overview
/app/lending/overview
```

When adding a page, match the link path from SubNav. For example, SubNav defines:
```ts
{ name: 'Bank Transactions', link: '/accounting/bank-transactions' }
```
The corresponding `APP_PAGES` entry would be:
```ts
{ path: 'accounting/bank-transactions', component: BankTransactionsPage }
```

## Adding a New Shell Page

For pages outside the app navigation (rare — most pages should be app pages):

1. Create `src/pages/[Name]Page.tsx` — the page component
2. Create `src/styles/[Name]Page.module.css` — the page stylesheet
3. Add an import to `App.tsx`: `import [Name]Page from './pages/[Name]Page'`
4. Add a `<Route>` element inside the `<Route element={<AppLayout />}>` block in `App.tsx`

## Page Naming Conventions

- **File names**: PascalCase with "Page" suffix — `BankTransactionsPage.tsx`, `InvoicesPage.tsx`
- **CSS files**: match the page file — `BankTransactionsPage.module.css`
- **App paths**: lowercase, hyphenated, matching SubNav — `accounting/bank-transactions`
- **Labels**: title case, short — `Bank Transactions`, `Invoices`

## CSS Import in Page Files

Each page imports its own module CSS using a relative path from `src/pages/`:

```tsx
import styles from '../styles/BankTransactionsPage.module.css'
```

Note the `../styles/` prefix — page files live one level deeper than `src/`.

## App.tsx Structure (AppShell Mode)

```tsx
// App.tsx — AppShell version with FusionShell layout.
import { HashRouter, Routes, Route, Outlet, Navigate } from 'react-router-dom'
import ErrorBoundary from './ErrorBoundary'
import { FusionProvider } from './contexts/fusion'
import FusionShell from './components/FusionShell'
import { FUSION_CONFIG } from './navigation'
import OnboardingPage from './pages/OnboardingPage'
import WorkspacePage from './pages/WorkspacePage'
import HomePage from './pages/HomePage'
import NotFoundPage from './pages/NotFoundPage'
import BankTransactionsPage from './pages/BankTransactionsPage'

function AppLayout() {
  return (
    <FusionShell businessName={FUSION_CONFIG.businessName}>
      <Outlet />
    </FusionShell>
  )
}

// APP_PAGES — add new app page routes here (managed by /page skill)
const APP_PAGES: { path: string; component: React.ComponentType }[] = [
  { path: 'accounting/bank-transactions', component: BankTransactionsPage },
]

export default function App() {
  return (
    <ErrorBoundary>
      <HashRouter>
        <FusionProvider pathPrefix={FUSION_CONFIG.pathPrefix || ''}>
          <Routes>
            <Route path="/onboarding" element={<OnboardingPage />} />
            <Route element={<AppLayout />}>
              <Route path="/" element={<Navigate to="/home" replace />} />
              <Route path="/home" element={<HomePage />} />
              <Route path="/workspace" element={<WorkspacePage />} />
              {APP_PAGES.map(({ path, component: Page }) => (
                <Route key={path} path={`/app/${path}`} element={<Page />} />
              ))}
              <Route path="/app/*" element={<NotFoundPage />} />
              <Route path="*" element={<NotFoundPage />} />
            </Route>
          </Routes>
        </FusionProvider>
      </HashRouter>
    </ErrorBoundary>
  )
}
```

## Styles Directory

```
src/styles/
├── App.module.css          ← Shell-level styles (minimal, for the router shell only)
├── HomePage.module.css     ← Home page styles
├── NotFoundPage.module.css ← Not-found placeholder styles
├── [Name]Page.module.css   ← Per-page styles
├── index.css               ← Global styles (do not edit)
├── fonts.css               ← Font imports (do not edit)
└── intuit.css              ← IDS design tokens (do not edit)
```

## Navigation Between Pages

The AppShell's SubNav sidebar handles all primary navigation. Clicking a SubNav item navigates to the corresponding `/app/...` path. The SubNav automatically highlights the active section and item based on the current URL.

### Programmatic Navigation

Use `useNavigate` from React Router when you need to navigate from within a page component:

```tsx
import { useNavigate } from 'react-router-dom'

const navigate = useNavigate()
navigate('/app/accounting/bank-transactions')
```

### Hash-Based URLs

Since the app uses HashRouter, all URLs are hash-based: `/#/app/accounting/bank-transactions`. The `path` values in `APP_PAGES` are relative (e.g. `'accounting/bank-transactions'`) and the router handles the `#` prefix automatically.

## Snapshot Awareness

Skills that snapshot the prototype must capture:
- `src/App.tsx`
- All files in `src/pages/`
- All `*.module.css` files in `src/styles/` (excluding `index.css`, `fonts.css`, `intuit.css`)
